<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="activator">Activator</a> - A <a href="#protein">protein</a> that binds <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> and <a href="#promoter">promotes</a> the <a href="#transcription">transcription</a> of nearby <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> (often directionally, on one side of the binding site, but sometimes bidirectionally). An activator can do this by recruiting <a href="#rna_polymerase_rna_p">RNA polymerase (RNA-P)</a>, opening a cell's <a href="#chromatin">chromatin</a> allowing access to the <a href="#promoter">promoter</a> region by <a href="#rna_polymerase_rna_p">RNA-P</a> (in <a href="#eukaryota">eukaryota</a>). This blocks a <a href="#repressor">repressor</a> from binding.